Here's the registration:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — one HttpClient / auth state for the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — new instance per request so pages get fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so each navigation push gets its own page
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient` and shared state (tokens, caches). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps auth consistent. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each page navigation should start with clean state (no stale data from a previous visit). |
| Pages | **Transient** | MAUI pages hold UI state; transient ensures a fresh page + ViewModel pair on every navigation. |

**Key rules of thumb:**

- **Singleton** — stateless services or services that *manage* shared state (HTTP clients, caches, logging).
- **Transient** — anything tied to a user interaction (pages, ViewModels). Cheap to create, no risk of stale state.
- **Scoped** — rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET). Useful only if you create explicit scopes yourself.

> ⚠️ Never inject a **transient** or **scoped** service into a **singleton** — the shorter-lived service effectively becomes a singleton too (captive dependency).
